post_text:
Voluntary Return of District Devices

We need your help! All students in grades 1-8 have/will be provided with a District-issued iPad (grades 1-2) or Chromebook (grades 3-8). Although we ordered devices for kindergarten, due to the disruption in the supply chain, our vendor has informed us that we will not receive these devices for several more weeks.

Since students will be working from home and the District-issued devices are not needed for use at school, we are asking any family that does not need their District-issued device to voluntarily return the device so we can redeploy it temporarily to a kindergarten student.

If we should return to in-person learning before our shipment arrives, we will collect the devices from our Kindergartners and return them to your child for use in school as well as at home.



Complete this form to indicate your ability and willingness to return your device.

If we should return to in-person learning before our shipment arrives, we will collect the devices from our Kindergartners and return them to your child for use in school as well as at home.



Complete this form to indicate your ability and willingness to return your device.

post_text:
2020-2021 CALENDAR CHANGES:
- September 1: Closed for all staff and students
- September 2-4: Teacher In Service Days
- September 8: First Day of School for Students
- March 8: School in session for students and staff
- May 28: School in session for students and staff
- Contingency Days in order: April 12; then, April 9, 8, 7, 6, and 5.
- At this time, all school days are Early Release Days for students.

CAMBIOS EN EL CALENDARIO 2020-2021:
- 1 de septiembre: cerrado para todo el personal y estudiantes
- 2-4 de septiembre: días de maestros en servicio
- 8 de septiembre: primer día de clases para estudiantes
- 8 de marzo: escuela en sesión para estudiantes y personal
- 28 de mayo: escuela en sesión para estudiantes y personal
- Días de contingencia en orden: 12 de abril; luego, 9 de abril, 8, 7, 6 y 5.
- En este momento, todos los días escolares son días de salida temprana para los estudiantes.

post_text:
Shout Out to... Torri, Grade 4!

"Shout out to our daughter Torri, Grade 4! It seems like only yesterday you were starting Pre-K at Copper Hill. Remember how on your first day of Kindergarten the steps of the bus were bigger than you! Remember your last few bus rides as a fourth grader showing kindness to the younger kids - you have grown out of Copper Hill but the lessons of Copper Hill have grown inside of you! Bring that caring and nurturing CH spirit with you as you take on life’s next step. We know you will succeed because you have already accomplished all that you have set your heart and mind to! We are proud of you and can’t wait to see what RFIS will teach you and what you will bring to RFIS! Congratulations!" Love. Dad and Mom

"A special thank you to all the CH staff for making the last 6 years an amazing educational experience for our daughter! She will miss all of you!"

post_text:
Shout Out to... Izabela, Grade 4!

"A huge shout out to our last 4th Grader at 💚Copper Hill Elementary School💚

✨ Izabela (Izzy) Arteaga✨

We are excited for your future as you move onto RFIS. We can’t believe how fast time has gone, you are one of a kind! We all love you princess!" Your Ohana, Dad, Mom, Logan, Xavier & Troy

"A shout out to the staff:

It is an extra sad year for our family. Izzy is the last of our 4 children to go through CH. We are so thankful for the staff that helped each one of our children. Each year was great and each year was memorable; they loved all of their teachers. We will miss the fun events, walking the halls, the Halloween parade, concerts and field day. So much work goes into teaching and all of these fun events. Thank you. Copper Hill, we will miss you and we thank you for all the memories.🤗

We still hear Mr. McPeek telling us, 'Today is Orientation, your first day with us and 4 years will pass quickly. Before you know it, they will be in RFIS.' It’s been a great 9 YEARS!"

Love, The Arteaga Family

Shout Out to...Megan!

"Shout out to our daughter ... MEGAN... for graduating from her elementary school FRANCIS A. DESMARES!

💙FAD💙FAD💙FAD💙FAD💙FAD💙

Megan began her journey as a Copper Hill student when she was just three years old. She’s been at FAD since kindergarten. Along the way, she has impressed all her teachers with her creativity, kindness, and intelligence and she has made many friendships.

💙 We are grateful for all she has learned and accomplished. She has grown to be a beautiful, determined, risk-taking, and energetic young lady. We are so proud of all of her accomplishments and know that many wonderful opportunities await her as she enters 5th grade at RFIS. 💙

We love you Megan!"

Love, Mom, Dad, Kaitlyn, and Brandon

💙 We are grateful for all she has learned and accomplished. She has grown to be a beautiful, determined, risk-taking, and energetic young lady. We are so proud of all of her accomplishments and know that many wonderful opportunities await her as she enters 5th grade at RFIS. 💙

We love you Megan!"

Love, Mom, Dad, Kaitlyn, and Brandon

post_text: Shout Out to...Charlotte, Grade 4! "We congratulate our daughter, Charlotte, on finishing 4th Grade at Copper Hill with grace and confidence. During her five years at Copper Hill, she has learned to advocate for herself, research and build creative innovations, sing about ants, pack her imaginary suitcase to travel around the world, help our community, make connections with new friends, write longer paragraphs than she’d like, and articulate what brings her joy. At home, she learned to do her own laundry from start to finish, feed and groom the puppy, plan and plant a vegetable and herb garden, ride a bike, survive a palate expander, teach her parents new technology, sew all kinds of things and put away her shoes. Her teachers have helped her grow and bloom. We love her more than she knows and we wish her much happiness in her coming years at RIFS." Love, Steve Persche and Caitlin Ryan Persche

Hi All! What do we need??? We could really use your help in preparing Student Protein and Snack Bags with the following contents to help our families who have children home from school:

Box of Crackers
Peanut Butter (2 jars)
Canned fruit (3 cans)
Canned Tuna or Chicken (2 cans)
Mac ‘n’ Cheese (2 boxes)
Water (2 bottles) (if possible)
Small Bags of Snacks (3 bags)

Bags can be dropped off at the Pantry side door from Monday-Thursday from 9-12. Call the pantry 908-788-5568 if can't drop off then. THANKS!!!.

NATIONAL SCHOOL COUNSELOR APPRECIATION
WEEK – FEBRUARY 3-7

We are so very proud of the many contributions our school counselors have made to our district. post_text: The Special Education Parent Advisory Group is hosting a workshop on developing IEPs with measurable goals on November 19 at 7 p.m. at J.P. Case Middle School. This workshop provides parents and professionals with strategies to create IEP’s with measurable annual goals and objectives as well as the required information regarding student progress. Step-by-step guidance in writing measurable goals to meet student needs is provided. Maintaining high expectations and accountability through the measurement of student progress is also discussed. https://www.frsd.k12.nj.us/cms/lib/NJ01001104/Centricity/Domain/64/IEP%20Measurable%20Goals%20Central%20flyer.pdf.

Seats are available -- Tuesday, November 19 -- Come out and hear Lisa Hamp, a survivor of the Virginia Tech shooting, speak during the 2nd Annual Hunterdon County School Safety Summit, 5:30 p.m. at J.P. Case Middle School.

This event is open to the public. All parents and staff members are invited to attend. This year's event will feature a very special keynote speaker -- Lisa Hamp from the Koshka Foundation. Bus Monitors Needed: Our Hunterdon County ESC Paraprofessional program is growing and expanding into Bus Monitoring!

We currently have openings for Bus Monitors in the Flemington-Raritan School District. Morning (8-9 a.m.) and afternoon (1:30-3 p.m. and 3:30-4:10 p.m.) routes available .

The successful candidate should possess knowledge of appropriate student contact practice and ability to ride a bus and/or van for various routes within the district. Criminal history background check and proof of US citizenship or legal resident alien status required.

For details email Christina Greaves at
cgreaves@hunterdonesc.org

Hunterdon County Prosecutors Office
September 9, 2019 at 6:41 PM ·

UPDATE: Juvenile has been found

MEDIA RELEASE - SEPTEMBER 9, 2019: ATTEMPT TO LOCATE MISSING JUVENILE

Acting Hunterdon County Prosecutor Michael J. Williams, Acting Chief of Detectives Frank R. Crisologo, and Raritan Township Police Chief Al Payne have announced that the missing juvenile from Raritan Township has been located and is unharmed. The investigation into the juvenile’s disappearance is ongoing.

Acting Prosecutor Williams stated, “I want to thank the detectives and police officers from the Hunterdon County Prosecutor’s Office, Raritan Township Police Department, Flemington Borough Police Department, New Jersey Department of Corrections K9 Unit, and the Federal Bureau of Investigation for their hard work and dedication during the search.”

post_text:
The Flemington–Raritan Regional School District is responsible for locating, identifying and evaluating any child residing in the school district who may be disabled regardless of the severity of the disability. Potentially disabled children include those who may be disabled due to physical, sensory, emotional, communication, cognitive or social difficulties.

Proof of Residency is required

These requirements apply to students attending non-public schools and highly mobile students with disabilities, such as migrant and homeless students, and to students who may be disabled even though they are advancing from grade to grade.
If eligible, students may qualify to special education and related services.

These related services include child study team evaluation services, self-contained special education classes, resource programs, inclusion classes, occupational therapy, physical therapy and speech and language therapy.

For more information, contact Flemington-Raritan Regional School District Special Services Department at (908) 284-7680.

post_text: During an assembly, Reading-Fleming Intermediate School celebrated the students' efforts to help our community. RFIS presented a check to the Amanda Styles Cirelli Foundation (ASCF) for 205 smile bags to bring smiles to the faces of children in the hospital. Students presented a check to the Jon Bon Jovi Soul Foundation and the Flemington Food Pantry for $3,624.50 for the Empty Bowls Project. Every bowl our students made and sold will now help feed a soul. The Huskies also presented the American Heart Association with a check for $2,049.44 for the Jump Rope for Heart initiative. Way to go, RFIS!

J.P. Case PTO
June 21, 2019 at 11:24 AM ·

The J.P. Case Middle School Eighth Grade Promotion Ceremony begins at 5:00 PM this Friday, June 21st. Students are to arrive back to school by 4:15 PM and report directly to the Auditorium with their cap and gown on.

All cars MUST have a visible parking pass to enter the J.P. Case parking lot. Upon entering the campus, please make sure the pass is visible for the Raritan Township Police Department. This will assist us with security procedures and help to ensure a swift entry into the parking lots.

For the safety of everyone, please make sure all students exit vehicles after parking on school grounds. No students should be exiting a car prior to entering campus.

At the conclusion of the ceremony please plan to meet your graduating child as follows:

Teams 8-1 and 8-2 in the Auditorium
Teams 8-3 and 8-4 in the Cafeteria

post_text: At Francis A. Desmares School, 4th-grade student Allison Gonzales-Asencio received the Hunterdon County School Counselor Association Student recognition award. She was recognized for her kind heart, her giving spirit, and her generosity toward others. Allison has made a positive impact on our school community. She is a tremendous role model and we honored her for her leadership. Congratulations, Allison!

post_text: J.P. Case Middle School 7th-grader Melanie Gonzalez Garcia has received an Enthusiastic Readers Award from the Hunterdon County Librarians Association. Melanie was honored at an awards ceremony for K-12 students on May 29. Melanie read 52 books this year! She is pictured with her teachers, Amy Martinez-Wright and Donna Cherkezian, and J.P. Case Library Clerk Lisa Lisiewski. Congratulations, Melanie!
